{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17522326","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17522326"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T14:44:25+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T14:44:25+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"13822"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"13822","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/13822"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0,0.76,0.06,0.04,0.13]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"6439"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"58267"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"6439","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/6439"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"13822"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"43715"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"78"},{"type":"tags","id":"2092"},{"type":"tags","id":"2386"},{"type":"tags","id":"2971"},{"type":"tags","id":"4965"},{"type":"tags","id":"4987"},{"type":"tags","id":"11625"},{"type":"tags","id":"11650"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"12756"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"58267","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/58267"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 68-year-old man presents to the General Practice clinic with a three-month history of tongue pain and burning, particularly when eating spicy foods. He follows a strict vegan diet. He has no significant medical history and takes no regular medications. On examination, he appears well with vital signs within normal limits. His tongue appears smooth, red, and glossy with loss of papillae (Image). The rest of the oral cavity examination is normal.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely diagnosis?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Oral candidiasis","Vitamin B12 deficiency","Folate deficiency","Lichen planus","Geographic tongue"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient presents with atrophic glossitis, characterised by a smooth, red, and painful tongue due to atrophy of the filiform papillae. Given his strict vegan diet and the clinical presentation, \u003Cstrong\u003Evitamin B12 deficiency\u003C/strong\u003E is the most likely underlying cause. B12 deficiency commonly presents with glossitis as one of its early manifestations, along with other features such as peripheral neuropathy and megaloblastic anaemia.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EFolate deficiency\u003C/strong\u003E can also cause atrophic glossitis and should be considered in the differential diagnosis. However, folate is readily available in plant-based foods, making B12 deficiency more likely as the primary cause in a vegan diet.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EGeographic tongue\u003C/strong\u003E (benign migratory glossitis) typically presents with irregular, map-like areas of depapillation with white borders that migrate over time. The appearance would be more patchy and less uniform than the presentation described here.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EOral candidiasis\u003C/strong\u003E typically presents with white, removable plaques on the tongue and oral mucosa. While it can cause burning symptoms, the appearance would be quite different from the smooth, red tongue seen in this case.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ELichen planus\u003C/strong\u003E affecting the tongue typically presents with white, lacy streaks (Wickham\u0027s striae) or erosive lesions. It would not cause the uniform smooth, red appearance described in this case.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe diagnosis can be confirmed with serum B12 levels, and if low, further investigation for the cause (including anti-intrinsic factor antibodies) may be warranted. Treatment involves B12 replacement, which can be given orally or parenterally depending on the underlying cause.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Atrophic glossitis presents with a smooth, red, painful tongue due to loss of papillae.","Vitamin B12 deficiency is a common cause of atrophic glossitis and should be investigated.","Other nutritional deficiencies including iron and folate can cause similar tongue appearances."],"references":["Kobayashi A, Iwasaki H. Pernicious anemia presenting as glossitis. CMAJ : Canadian Medical Association Journal [Internet]. 2020 Apr 20;192(16):E434. Available at: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC7207183/","\u200c"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"43715"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"13822"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"20769"}]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"media","id":"20769","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/20769"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/duHUqOZdX4OVYco2b5jb8WFsOSxbR9.jpg","thumbUrl":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/duHUqOZdX4OVYco2b5jb8WFsOSxbR9.jpg","isProcessed":true,"width":1024,"height":768}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"43715","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/43715"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-10-30T12:35:35+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-10-30T12:36:15+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"6439"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"58267"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"25","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/25"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc68\u200d\ud83d\udc69\u200d\ud83d\udc66","name":"General